I have a use case involving game data, where I'd like to define a tuple property in my schema that includes a reference to an object.  Moreover, this property is actually a _list_ of tuples.  So the schema would look something like:

```python
type Item {
    required name: str;
}

type LootTable {
    required name: str;
    multi drops: tuple<Item, int32>;  # <Item link, Probability>
}
```

Currently, the only way I can _sort of_ solve this is by introducing a new type called `ItemProbability` (for example) instead of a tuple:

```python
type ItemProbability {
    item: Item;
    prob: int32;
}
```

This presents its own difficulties, however, as I now have to define <Item, Probability> pairings as individual records in a new `ItemProbability` table, and then link them one-by-one in a `LootTable` which is quite backwards from the normal workflow you might expect.

This presents all sorts of challenges in managing the data going forward.  In keeping with my example, imagine a situation where you have 100 different enemies in the game, each with their own individual loot tables, and each loot table might define dozens of potential Item drops, with their corresponding drop probabilities (in the form of dozens of `ItemProbability` link records per loot table).

You'll end up with an `ItemProbability` table that's a mess of replicated data, since it doesn't really make sense to track each individual <Item, Probability> pairing in its own table - this pairing data should realistically have been embedded in each individual `LootTable` object in a `multi` list of tuples.  You might have 10 different enemies that all have a "Probability = 7" chance to drop "Generic Sword", for example.  Now you've got 10 distinct, yet identical records in the `ItemProbability` table and no way to figure out which one goes with which loot table, unless you want to start throwing backlinks into the mix which feels completely overboard for something as simple as a 2-element tuple that you ideally wanted embedded in the `LootTable` in the first place.

There's one other piece to this puzzle that would be super helpful, in the event that this feature gets implemented, and that would be EdgeDB UI improvements to show `multi` properties in a more human-readable presentation in the table views.  I've commented on this in more detail in the UI project here:  https://github.com/edgedb/edgedb-ui/issues/51#issuecomment-1762697890

This issue was also briefly discussed in Issue #5689, but since that issue was closed, I wanted to make a formal feature request for this so that it might be better tracked, and perhaps added to the roadmap and slotted into a future release at some point.

Side-note for the documentation folks:  It might be worth updating the page on [Tuples](https://www.edgedb.com/docs/datamodel/primitives#tuples) to reflect that the following documentation only applies for queries, and not for schemas:

> Tuple elements can be any type, including primitives, objects, arrays, and other tuples.

